    "## Background and Prior Work"
   ]
  },
  {
   "attachments": {},
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "Air quality can be a major factor in human health. Air quality is typically measured by the Air Quality Index (AQI), which measures the levels of five pollutants: ground-level ozone, nitrogen dioxide (NO2), sulfur dioxide (SO2), carbon monoxide (CO), and aerosols/particulate matter (PM) <a name=\"cite_ref-1\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-1). One leading contributor to poor air quality in urban areas comes from the transportation sector, especially exhaust from gasoline powered cars. Cars release many air pollutants, such as nitrogen dioxides (which includes NO2), CO, PM, formaldehyde, and carbon compounds that contribute to ground level ozone formation <a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-2). Most of the pollutants measured by AQI are released by cars, so it stands to reason that how much gasoline is consumed is linked to air quality. In this project, we would like to investigate if the cost of gasoline is related to air quality. \n",
    "\n",
    "One previous study investigated the cost of gasoline and air pollution in Brisbane, Australia from 2010-2013 <a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-3). They found that diesel costs specifically are negatively correlated with carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxide (NOx) levels, while PM levels were not related. They found that gasoline prices were not correlated with air quality, only diesel. The authors claimed that cars emit a lower proportion of PM compared to CO/NOx, and thus the effect of driving cars on PM is negligible. They also suggest that diesel engines emit a larger proportion of NOx compared to gas powered cars, and that the behavior of drivers of diesel engines, such as trucks, is more sensitive to changes in fuel price. However, another study, covering 133 countries, found that prices of both diesel and gasoline have a negative effect on PM2.5 (a type of particulate matter) <a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-4). \n",
    "\n",
    "A study done on diesel vs. gasoline cars in Europe did find that the emissions of diesel engines are different than those of gasoline engines under normal driving conditions, but not in a simple “one type creates more emissions than the other” way <a name=\"cite_ref-5\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-5). Diesel engines were found to have less NOx and PM emissions during most periods, but significantly peaks during times of high acceleration or low speed, when fuel efficiency is low. This is related to the temperature of the catalytic converter, which transforms harmful exhaust pollutants into less environmentally damaging gases. During periods of high acceleration or low speed, the temperature of the catalytic converter is lower, decreasing its conversion efficiency. \n",
    "\n",
    "Aside from prices of fuels, there are many other factors that influence the emissions of cars. One consideration is lag in the effect of price changes: people only refill their gas every so often, so when the gas prices change, the effect is not felt until people need to refuel their vehicles <a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-3). Another consideration is the use of alternative fuels. If people are less willing to use gasoline in their cars, they may turn to other fuels that may release more pollutants, which is opposite of the expected trend <a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-4). Additionally, gasoline isn’t used purely for powering cars <a name=\"cite_ref-4\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-4). An aspect of time and technology must also be considered. The technologies used in cars have generally led to a decrease in pollutants in the modern era, as cars become more efficient in fuel usage, catalytic converter performance improves, and electric vehicles become more popular <a name=\"cite_ref-2\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-2). Furthermore, the effect of human behavior and traffic is important as well. If less people are driving because of high fuel prices, traffic is better and people can drive with better fuel efficiency <a name=\"cite_ref-3\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-3). This also reduces the periods of low speed and high acceleration <a name=\"cite_ref-5\"></a>[<sup>1</sup>](#cite_note-5), decreasing emissions. \n",
    "\n",
    "1. <a name=\"cite_note-1\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-1) NOAA. (31 Aug 2025) How Is Air Quality Measured? https://www.nesdis.noaa.gov/about/k-12-education/dust-ash-fire-smoke/how-air-quality-measured \n",
    "2. <a name=\"cite_note-2\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-2) EPA. (30 Mar 2026) Smog Vehicle Emissions. https://www.epa.gov/greenvehicles/smog-vehicle-emissions \n"
    "3. <a name=\"cite_note-3\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-3) Barnett, A.; Knibbs, L. (16 Feb 2014) Higher fuel prices are asssociated with lower air pollution levels. *Environment International* https://doi.org/10.1016/j.envint.2014.01.029 \n"
    "4. <a name=\"cite_note-4\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-4) Mayr, K.; Rentschler, J. (Apr 2023) Fossil Fuel Prices and Air Pollution: Evidence from a Panel of 133 Countries. *World Bank Group* https://openknowledge.worldbank.org/server/api/core/bitstreams/90ce4cc1-2fd1-4986-b1fc-126f3a71693b/content \n"
    "5. <a name=\"cite_note-5\"></a> [^](#cite_ref-5) Gao, J. et al. (20 Dec 2021) Comparison of NOx and PN emissions between Euro 6 petrol and diesel passenger cars under real-world driving conditions. *Science of the Total Environment* https://doi.org/10.1016/j.scitotenv.2021.149789 \n"
   ]
